PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5stats_11descriptive_44hmean, "\n    Calculate the harmonic mean of a data set and optionally visualize the \n    data distribution through a histogram.\n\n    The harmonic mean, useful for rates and ratios, is less influenced by\n    large outliers compared to the arithmetic mean. It is defined as the \n    reciprocal of the arithmetic mean of the reciprocals of the data points.\n\n    .. math::\n        H = \014rac{n}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n} \014rac{1}{x_i}}\n\n    Where :math:`H` is the harmonic mean, :math:`n` is the number of observations, \n    and :math:`x_i` are the data points.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    data : DataFrame or ArrayLike\n        The data for which the harmonic mean is desired. Can be a pandas DataFrame \n        or a numpy array. If a DataFrame and `columns` is specified, only the \n        selected columns are used for the calculation.\n    columns : List[str], optional\n        Specific columns to use for the calculation if `data` is a DataFrame.\n    as_frame : bool, optional\n        If True and `data` is ArrayLike, converts `data` into a DataFrame\n        using `columns` as column names. Ignored if `data` is already a DataFrame.\n    axis : {None, 0, 1}, optional\n        Axis along which to compute the harmonic mean:\n        - `None`: Harmonic mean is calculated using all values in the input \n          array, flattening it if necessary. This is the default behavior.\n        - `0`: Compute the harmonic mean along columns for a DataFrame or a \n          2D numpy array. This results in a harmonic mean value for each column.\n        - `1`: Compute the harmonic mean along rows for a DataFrame or a 2D \n          numpy array. This results in a harmonic mean value for each row.\n        If `data` is a DataFrame and specific `columns` are selected, the \n        computation will consider only the selected columns. If `as_frame` \n        is True, the result will be returned as a pandas DataFrame; otherwise, \n        it will be returned in the form of a numpy array ""or a scalar value, \n        depending on the dimensionality of the input.\n    view : bool, optional\n        If True, displays a histogram of the data set to visualize its\n        distribution. Default is False.\n    cmap : str, optional\n        Colormap for the histogram. Default is 'viridis'.\n    fig_size : Tuple[int, int], optional\n        Size of the figure for the histogram. Default is (10, 6).\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    h_mean : float\n        The harmonic mean of the data set.\n\n    Raises\n    ------\n    ValueError\n        If any data point is less than or equal to zero.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import hmean\n    >>> hmean([1, 2, 4])\n    1.7142857142857142\n\n    >>> hmean(np.array([2.5, 3.0, 10.0]))\n    3.5294117647058822\n    \n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [2.5, 3.0, 10.0], 'B': [1.5, 2.0, 8.0]})\n    >>> hmean(df, columns=['A'])\n    3.5999999999999996\n   \n    See Also\n    --------\n    scipy.stats.hmean : Harmonic mean function in SciPy for one-dimensional arrays.\n    gofast.stats.mean : Arithmetic mean function.\n    ");

 1921: ):
 1922:     """
 1923:     Calculate the harmonic mean of a data set and optionally visualize the
 1924:     data distribution through a histogram.
 1925: 
 1926:     The harmonic mean, useful for rates and ratios, is less influenced by
 1927:     large outliers compared to the arithmetic mean. It is defined as the
 1928:     reciprocal of the arithmetic mean of the reciprocals of the data points.
 1929: 
 1930:     .. math::
 1931:         H = \frac{n}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{1}{x_i}}
 1932: 
 1933:     Where :math:`H` is the harmonic mean, :math:`n` is the number of observations,
 1934:     and :math:`x_i` are the data points.
 1935: 
 1936:     Parameters
 1937:     ----------
 1938:     data : DataFrame or ArrayLike
 1939:         The data for which the harmonic mean is desired. Can be a pandas DataFrame
 1940:         or a numpy array. If a DataFrame and `columns` is specified, only the
 1941:         selected columns are used for the calculation.
 1942:     columns : List[str], optional
 1943:         Specific columns to use for the calculation if `data` is a DataFrame.
 1944:     as_frame : bool, optional
 1945:         If True and `data` is ArrayLike, converts `data` into a DataFrame
 1946:         using `columns` as column names. Ignored if `data` is already a DataFrame.
 1947:     axis : {None, 0, 1}, optional
 1948:         Axis along which to compute the harmonic mean:
 1949:         - `None`: Harmonic mean is calculated using all values in the input
 1950:           array, flattening it if necessary. This is the default behavior.
 1951:         - `0`: Compute the harmonic mean along columns for a DataFrame or a
 1952:           2D numpy array. This results in a harmonic mean value for each column.
 1953:         - `1`: Compute the harmonic mean along rows for a DataFrame or a 2D
 1954:           numpy array. This results in a harmonic mean value for each row.
 1955:         If `data` is a DataFrame and specific `columns` are selected, the
 1956:         computation will consider only the selected columns. If `as_frame`
 1957:         is True, the result will be returned as a pandas DataFrame; otherwise,
 1958:         it will be returned in the form of a numpy array or a scalar value,
 1959:         depending on the dimensionality of the input.
 1960:     view : bool, optional
 1961:         If True, displays a histogram of the data set to visualize its
 1962:         distribution. Default is False.
 1963:     cmap : str, optional
 1964:         Colormap for the histogram. Default is 'viridis'.
 1965:     fig_size : Tuple[int, int], optional
 1966:         Size of the figure for the histogram. Default is (10, 6).
 1967: 
 1968:     Returns
 1969:     -------
 1970:     h_mean : float
 1971:         The harmonic mean of the data set.
 1972: 
 1973:     Raises
 1974:     ------
 1975:     ValueError
 1976:         If any data point is less than or equal to zero.
 1977: 
 1978:     Examples
 1979:     --------
 1980:     >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import hmean
 1981:     >>> hmean([1, 2, 4])
 1982:     1.7142857142857142
 1983: 
 1984:     >>> hmean(np.array([2.5, 3.0, 10.0]))
 1985:     3.5294117647058822
 1986: 
 1987:     >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [2.5, 3.0, 10.0], 'B': [1.5, 2.0, 8.0]})
 1988:     >>> hmean(df, columns=['A'])
 1989:     3.5999999999999996
 1990: 
 1991:     See Also
 1992:     --------
 1993:     scipy.stats.hmean : Harmonic mean function in SciPy for one-dimensional arrays.
 1994:     gofast.stats.mean : Arithmetic mean function.
 1995:     """

Can be a list, numpy \n        array, or pandas DataFrame containing valid numeric values.\n    columns : list of str, optional\n        List of column names to consider for the calculation if `data` is a \n        DataFrame. If not provided, all numeric columns are considered.\n    axis : optional, {index (0), columns (1)}\n         Axis for the function to be applied on. Default is 0.\n    as_frame : bool, default False\n        Indicates whether to convert the input data to a DataFrame before \n        proceeding with the calculation. Relevant when input data is not \n        already a DataFrame.\n    view : bool, default=False\n        If True, visualizes the statistical analysis results or the data \n        distribution.\n    cmap : str, default='viridis'\n        Colormap for the visualization. Only applicable if `view` is True.\n    as_frame : bool, default=False\n        If True, the result is returned as a pandas DataFrame or Series, depending\n        on the dimensionality of the output. Otherwise, the result is returned in\n        its native format (e.g., float, np.ndarray).\n    fig_size : Optional[Tuple[int, int]], default=None\n        Size of the figure for the visualization. Only applicable if `view` \n        is True.\n    **kws : dict\n        Additional keyword arguments for data preprocessing, not directly \n        used in range calculation but may be used for data sanitization.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    range_value : float or pd.Series\n        The calculated range of the provided data. Returns a single fl""oat if \n        the data is one-dimensional or a pandas Series if the input is a DataFrame \n        and `as_frame` is True, showing the range for each specified column.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import get_range\n    >>> data_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n    >>> get_range(data_array)\n    4\n\n    >>> data_df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [2, 5, 8], 'B': [1, 4, 7]})\n    >>> get_range(data_df, columns=['A'])\n    6\n\n    >>> get_range(data_df, as_frame=True)\n    A    6\n    B    6\n    dtype: int64\n    \n    >>> data_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n    >>> print(get_range(data_array, view=True))\n\n    >>> data_df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [2, 5, 8], 'B': [1, 4, 7]})\n    >>> print(get_range(data_df, as_frame=True, view=True, fig_size=(8, 4)))\n\n    Note\n    ----\n    The function aims to provide a straightforward way to compute the range \n    of a dataset, enhancing data analysis tasks.  2076:     """
 2077:     Calculates the range of numeric data provided either as an array-like
 2078:     structure or within a pandas DataFrame.
 2079: 
 2080:     This function computes the difference between the maximum and minimum
 2081:     values in the dataset, optionally focusing on specified columns when
 2082:     dealing with DataFrames.
 2083: 
 2084:     Parameters
 2085:     ----------
 2086:     data : ArrayLike or DataFrame
 2087:         The input data from which to calculate the range. Can be a list, numpy
 2088:         array, or pandas DataFrame containing valid numeric values.
 2089:     columns : list of str, optional
 2090:         List of column names to consider for the calculation if `data` is a
 2091:         DataFrame. If not provided, all numeric columns are considered.
 2092:     axis : optional, {index (0), columns (1)}
 2093:          Axis for the function to be applied on. Default is 0.
 2094:     as_frame : bool, default False
 2095:         Indicates whether to convert the input data to a DataFrame before
 2096:         proceeding with the calculation. Relevant when input data is not
 2097:         already a DataFrame.
 2098:     view : bool, default=False
 2099:         If True, visualizes the statistical analysis results or the data
 2100:         distribution.
 2101:     cmap : str, default='viridis'
 2102:         Colormap for the visualization. Only applicable if `view` is True.
 2103:     as_frame : bool, default=False
 2104:         If True, the result is returned as a pandas DataFrame or Series, depending
 2105:         on the dimensionality of the output. Otherwise, the result is returned in
 2106:         its native format (e.g., float, np.ndarray).
 2107:     fig_size : Optional[Tuple[int, int]], default=None
 2108:         Size of the figure for the visualization. Only applicable if `view`
 2109:         is True.
 2110:     **kws : dict
 2111:         Additional keyword arguments for data preprocessing, not directly
 2112:         used in range calculation but may be used for data sanitization.
 2113: 
 2114:     Returns
 2115:     -------
 2116:     range_value : float or pd.Series
 2117:         The calculated range of the provided data. Returns a single float if
 2118:         the data is one-dimensional or a pandas Series if the input is a DataFrame
 2119:         and `as_frame` is True, showing the range for each specified column.
 2120: 
 2121:     Examples
 2122:     --------
 2123:     >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import get_range
 2124:     >>> data_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
 2125:     >>> get_range(data_array)
 2126:     4
 2127: 
 2128:     >>> data_df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [2, 5, 8], 'B': [1, 4, 7]})
 2129:     >>> get_range(data_df, columns=['A'])
 2130:     6
 2131: 
 2132:     >>> get_range(data_df, as_frame=True)
 2133:     A    6
 2134:     B    6
 2135:     dtype: int64
 2136: 
 2137:     >>> data_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
 2138:     >>> print(get_range(data_array, view=True))
 2139: 
 2140:     >>> data_df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [2, 5, 8], 'B': [1, 4, 7]})
 2141:     >>> print(get_range(data_df, as_frame=True, view=True, fig_size=(8, 4)))
 2142: 
 2143:     Note
 2144:     ----
 2145:     The function aims to provide a straightforward way to compute the range

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5stats_11descriptive_52describe, "\n    Generates a comprehensive summary of descriptive statistics for a \n    given dataset.\n    \n    This function provides an easy way to get an overview of basic descriptive \n    statistics including mean, median, mode, min, max, etc., for numerical data \n    in a DataFrame or an array-like structure. It's particularly useful for \n    preliminary data analysis and understanding the distribution of data points.\n    \n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    data : ArrayLike or pd.DataFrame\n        The input data for which descriptive statistics are to be calculated.\n        Can be a Pandas DataFrame or any array-like structure containing \n        numerical data.\n    columns : List[str], optional\n        Specific columns to include in the analysis if `data` is a DataFrame.\n        If None, all columns are included. Default is None.\n    dtypes_include : 'all', list-like of dtypes or None (default='all'), optional\n        A white list of data types to include in the result. \n        Ignored for ArrayLike input.\n        - 'all' : All columns of the input will be included in the output.\n        - A list-like of dtypes : Limits the data to the provided data types.\n          For example, [np.number, 'datetime'] will include only numeric and \n          datetime data.\n    dtypes_exclude : list-like of dtypes or None (default=None), optional\n        A black list of data types to exclude from the result. \n        Ignored for ArrayLike input.\n    as_frame : bool, default=True\n        If True, the input array-like structure is converted to a Pandas DataFrame\n        before calculating the descriptive statistics. This is useful if the input\n        is a structured array or a sequence of sequences and you want the output\n        in the form of a DataFrame.\n    view : bool, optional\n        If True, generates a visualization of the descriptive statistics \n        based on `plot_type`.  Default is False.\n    orient: str, {None,'h'}\n       Orientation of ""the boxplot. Use 'h' for horizontal orientation otherwise \n       the default is vertical (``None``). \n       \n    plot_type : Optional[str], optional\n        Specifies the type of plot for visualization: 'box', 'hist', or \n        'density'. Ignored if `view` is False. Default is 'box'.\n    cmap : str, optional\n        The colormap used for plotting. Default is 'viridis'.\n    fig_size : Optional[Tuple[int, int]], optional\n        The size of the figure for the plot. Default is (10, 6).\n    **kwargs : dict\n        Additional keyword arguments to be passed to the\n        `pd.DataFrame.describe` method.\n    \n    Returns\n    -------\n    pd.DataFrame or pd.Series\n        The descriptive statistics of the data. Returns a DataFrame if `as_frame` is True\n        or if `data` is a DataFrame; otherwise, returns a Series.\n    \n    Examples\n    --------\n    \n    >>> import numpy as np\n    >>> import pandas as pd\n    >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import describe\n    >>> data = np.random.rand(100, 4)\n    >>> describe(data, as_frame=True)\n    \n    >>> import pandas as pd\n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])\n    >>> describe(df, columns=['A', 'B'])\n    \n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])\n    >>> describe(df, columns=['A', 'B'], view=True, plot_type='hist')\n    Note\n    ----\n    This function is a convenient wrapper around `pd.DataFrame.describe`,\n    allowing for additional flexibility and ease of use. It's designed to\n    work seamlessly with both array-like structures and Pandas DataFrames,\n    making it a versatile tool for initial data exploration.\n    ");

 2234:     """
 2235:     Generates a comprehensive summary of descriptive statistics for a
 2236:     given dataset.
 2237: 
 2238:     This function provides an easy way to get an overview of basic descriptive
 2239:     statistics including mean, median, mode, min, max, etc., for numerical data
 2240:     in a DataFrame or an array-like structure. It's particularly useful for
 2241:     preliminary data analysis and understanding the distribution of data points.
 2242: 
 2243:     Parameters
 2244:     ----------
 2245:     data : ArrayLike or pd.DataFrame
 2246:         The input data for which descriptive statistics are to be calculated.
 2247:         Can be a Pandas DataFrame or any array-like structure containing
 2248:         numerical data.
 2249:     columns : List[str], optional
 2250:         Specific columns to include in the analysis if `data` is a DataFrame.
 2251:         If None, all columns are included. Default is None.
 2252:     dtypes_include : 'all', list-like of dtypes or None (default='all'), optional
 2253:         A white list of data types to include in the result.
 2254:         Ignored for ArrayLike input.
 2255:         - 'all' : All columns of the input will be included in the output.
 2256:         - A list-like of dtypes : Limits the data to the provided data types.
 2257:           For example, [np.number, 'datetime'] will include only numeric and
 2258:           datetime data.
 2259:     dtypes_exclude : list-like of dtypes or None (default=None), optional
 2260:         A black list of data types to exclude from the result.
 2261:         Ignored for ArrayLike input.
 2262:     as_frame : bool, default=True
 2263:         If True, the input array-like structure is converted to a Pandas DataFrame
 2264:         before calculating the descriptive statistics. This is useful if the input
 2265:         is a structured array or a sequence of sequences and you want the output
 2266:         in the form of a DataFrame.
 2267:     view : bool, optional
 2268:         If True, generates a visualization of the descriptive statistics
 2269:         based on `plot_type`.  Default is False.
 2270:     orient: str, {None,'h'}
 2271:        Orientation of the boxplot. Use 'h' for horizontal orientation otherwise
 2272:        the default is vertical (``None``).
 2273: 
 2274:     plot_type : Optional[str], optional
 2275:         Specifies the type of plot for visualization: 'box', 'hist', or
 2276:         'density'. Ignored if `view` is False. Default is 'box'.
 2277:     cmap : str, optional
 2278:         The colormap used for plotting. Default is 'viridis'.
 2279:     fig_size : Optional[Tuple[int, int]], optional
 2280:         The size of the figure for the plot. Default is (10, 6).
 2281:     **kwargs : dict
 2282:         Additional keyword arguments to be passed to the
 2283:         `pd.DataFrame.describe` method.
 2284: 
 2285:     Returns
 2286:     -------
 2287:     pd.DataFrame or pd.Series
 2288:         The descriptive statistics of the data. Returns a DataFrame if `as_frame` is True
 2289:         or if `data` is a DataFrame; otherwise, returns a Series.
 2290: 
 2291:     Examples
 2292:     --------
 2293: 
 2294:     >>> import numpy as np
 2295:     >>> import pandas as pd
 2296:     >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import describe
 2297:     >>> data = np.random.rand(100, 4)
 2298:     >>> describe(data, as_frame=True)
 2299: 
 2300:     >>> import pandas as pd
 2301:     >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])
 2302:     >>> describe(df, columns=['A', 'B'])
 2303: 
 2304:     >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])
 2305:     >>> describe(df, columns=['A', 'B'], view=True, plot_type='hist')
 2306:     Note
 2307:     ----
 2308:     This function is a convenient wrapper around `pd.DataFrame.describe`,
 2309:     allowing for additional flexibility and ease of use. It's designed to
 2310:     work seamlessly with both array-like structures and Pandas DataFrames,
 2311:     making it a versatile tool for initial data exploration.
 2312:     """
 2313:     # Convert array-like input to DataFrame if necessary

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5stats_11descriptive_56z_scores, "\n    Computes the Z-scores for each data point in a dataset. \n    \n    Optionally visualizes the distribution.\n    \n    Z-scores, or standard scores, indicate how many standard deviations an \n    element is from the mean. This function can standardize a single array of\n    values or specific columns within a pandas DataFrame.\n    \n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    data : Union[ArrayLike, pd.DataFrame]\n        The dataset for which to calculate Z-scores. Can be a list, \n        numpy array, or pandas DataFrame.\n        \n    columns : Optional[List[str]] (default=None)\n        Specifies the columns within a DataFrame for which to calculate Z-scores. \n        Applicable only when `data` is a DataFrame. If None, Z-scores for \n        all columns are calculated.\n        \n    as_frame : bool (default=True)\n        When True, returns the result as a pandas DataFrame or Series \n        (depending on the input).  2362:     **kws):
 2363:     """
 2364:     Computes the Z-scores for each data point in a dataset.
 2365: 
 2366:     Optionally visualizes the distribution.
 2367: 
 2368:     Z-scores, or standard scores, indicate how many standard deviations an
 2369:     element is from the mean. This function can standardize a single array of
 2370:     values or specific columns within a pandas DataFrame.
 2371: 
 2372:     Parameters
 2373:     ----------
 2374:     data : Union[ArrayLike, pd.DataFrame]
 2375:         The dataset for which to calculate Z-scores. Can be a list,
 2376:         numpy array, or pandas DataFrame.
 2377: 
 2378:     columns : Optional[List[str]] (default=None)
 2379:         Specifies the columns within a DataFrame for which to calculate Z-scores.
 2380:         Applicable only when `data` is a DataFrame. If None, Z-scores for
 2381:         all columns are calculated.
 2382: 
 2383:     as_frame : bool (default=True)
 2384:         When True, returns the result as a pandas DataFrame or Series
 2385:         (depending on the input). Useful for maintaining DataFrame structure
 2386:         in the output.
 2387: 
 2388:     view : bool (default=False)
 2389:         If True, generates a visualization of the Z-scores distribution.
 2390:         The type of visualization is determined by the `plot_type` parameter.
 2391: 
 2392:     plot_type : Optional[str] (default='hist')
 2393:         Specifies the type of plot for visualization:
 2394:         - 'hist': Histogram of the Z-scores distribution.
 2395:         - 'boxplot': Box plot showing the quartiles and outliers.
 2396:         - 'density': Density plot for a smooth distribution curve.
 2397: 
 2398:     cmap : str (default='viridis')
 2399:         The colormap for the visualization plot. Applicable only if `view` is True.
 2400: 
 2401:     orient: str, {None,'h'}
 2402:        Orientation of the boxplot. Use 'h' for horizontal orientation otherwise
 2403:        the default is vertical (``None``).
 2404: 
 2405:     fig_size : Optional[Tuple[int, int]] (default=(8, 6))
 2406:         Size of the figure for the visualization plot. Applicable only if `view` is True.
 2407: 
 2408:     **kws : dict
 2409:         Additional keyword arguments for customization, not directly used
 2410:         in Z-score calculation.
 2411: 
 2412:     Returns
 2413:     -------
 2414:     Union[np.ndarray, pd.DataFrame]
 2415:         The Z-scores of the provided data. Returns a numpy array if the data
 2416:         is one-dimensional or if `as_frame` is False. Returns a pandas DataFrame
 2417:         if the input is a DataFrame and `as_frame` is True.
 2418: 
 2419:     Examples
 2420:     --------
 2421:     >>> import numpy as np
 2422:     >>> import pandas as pd
 2423:     >>> from gofast.stats.descriptive import z_scores
 2424: 
 2425:     Calculating Z-scores for an array:
 2426:     >>> data_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
 2427:     >>> print(z_scores(data_array))
 2428:     [-1.41421356, -0.70710678, 0., 0.70710678, 1.41421356]
 2429: 
 2430:     Calculating and visualizing Z-scores for DataFrame columns:
 2431:     >>> data_df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 'B': [4, 5, 6]})
 2432:     >>> z_scores(data_df, as_frame=True, view=True, plot_type='boxt')
 2433: 
 2434:     >>> data_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
 2435:     >>> z_scores(data_array)
 2436:     [-1.41421356, -0.70710678, 0., 0.70710678, 1.41421356]
 2437: 
 2438:     >>> data_df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 'B': [4, 5, 6]})
 2439:     >>> z_scores(data_df, as_frame=True)
 2440:              A         B
 2441:     0 -1.224745 -1.224745
 2442:     1  0.000000  0.000000
 2443:     2  1.224745  1.224745
 2444: 
 2445:     Note
 2446:     ----
 2447:     The Z-score is a powerful tool for data standardization, making it easier
 2448:     to compare measurements across different scales. Visualization options
